eicestershire or Staffordshire; or possibly from <i>Coat</i> in Somerset, <i>Cote</i> in Oxford and Yorkshire, with excrescent <i>-s</i>; or possibly from any of numerous other places similarly named from the new Middle English plural form <i>cotes</i> of Old English <i>cot</i> (plural <i>cotu</i>) ‘cottage’, also ‘shelter’, and sometimes ‘woodman's hut’. It is possible that some bearers may be from a place whose current name is from the dative plural form of this word, <i>cotum</i>, for example Coatham (Durham) or Cottam, Cotham (Nottinghamshire), or from the plural of the related weak noun <i>cote</i>, plural <i>coten</i>. Cotham (Nottinghamshire) is early recorded as <i>Cotes</i>, and Coton (Cambridgeshire, Derbyshire, Northamptonshire) have many similar spellings. See also   Coate  . There are very small places in Midlothian, East Lothian, and Fife called <i>Coates</i>, but the surname seems rarely if ever to be Scottish in origin.","Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Kotz   or perhaps German   Koths  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Coats","meanings":["English: variant of   Coates  .","Scottish: variant of   Coutts  ."]},{"name":"Coate","meanings":["English (Somerset): habitational name from any of several places called from Old or Middle English <i>cot(e)</i> ‘cottage’, such as Coat (Somerset), Coate (Wiltshire), or Cote (Oxfordshire). The placenames literally meant ‘the cottage(s) or hut(s)’, hence the medieval surname forms <i>de la Cote</i>, <i>atte Cote</i>. It is possible that some of the medieval surnames denoted someone who lived at a particular cottage, known as such, within a village or one who worked from a hut, but a topographic origin is most likely for the modern hereditary surname. Medieval and post-medieval forms of the placename often vacillate between singular and plural versions. See   Coates  .","Americanized form of German   Koth   or some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Cottage","meanings":["English: from a local pronunciation of <b>Cottis</b>, which is probably a variant of   Coates  . The change in the final syllable is similar to that in   Surridge   for earlier <i>Surreis</i>. There is no evidence to support the view in some dictionaries that it derives from Middle English <i>cotage</i> ‘cottage’.","Americanized form of Croatian and Serbian <b>Katić</b> (see   Katic  )."]}]},{"name":"Catherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."],"variants":[{"name":"Catheryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["Greek: Same as Catherine."]},{"name":"Catharin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Catharine","meanings":["Greek: Pure."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Catherine Coates was born in 1350, in Coates, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Cotes II, was 30 and her mother, Dorothy Shrily, was 30. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir Richard Chamberlain II."},"et":{"1350–":"1350–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1310–1391":"1310–1391","1368–1410":"1368–1410","1320–1356":"1320–1356","1320–1360":"1320–1360","1368":"1368","1356":"1356","1410":"1410","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","about 1368":"umbes 1368","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1391":"1391","Coastes, Northhamptonshire, England":"Castor, Northamptonshire, England","Coates, Gloucestershire, England":"Coates, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdo